        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough | Kent</placeName>
                    <date>June 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I am much obliged by your note of the 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. informing me that a draft of 194’8’1 has been placed to my credit at Robarts.</p>
<p>I will not fail to inform my Father regarding the trust &amp; L<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Yarborough.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>My sister enjoyed her visit into Lincolnshire extremely &amp; brought home a very flourishing account of all that she saw.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Many thanks for your kind offers about the sea-bathing place, but I fear at present it will not be in our power to go anywhere.</p>
<p>Pray believe me | My dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | C. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> J. Higgins Es<hi rend="superscript">q</hi></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is based on an entry of 6 June 1848 in CD’s Investment Book (Down House MS) for the sum of £199 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. He also recorded a payment of £5 to the Beesby School in his Account Book (Down House MS). The deduction of the latter amount would account for the sum mentioned in the letter.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5246.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Anderson Worsley</ref>, Earl of Yarborough, whose seat was Brocklesby Park, North Lincolnshire. There is no indication in Robert Waring Darwin’s Investment Book (Down House MS) that he had any financial dealings with Lord Yarborough. It is possible that one of Lord Yarborough’s farms was available to rent or purchase, see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1185.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Higgins, 14 June [1848]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Susan Darwin. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Emma Darwin, [20–1 May 1848]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
